      <h1>Traditional vs. Roth 401(k): Tax Differences</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>Jun 19, 2026</span><span>·</span><span>6 min read</span></div>
      <p class="article-intro">Deciding between a Traditional and a Roth 401(k) is one of the most important decisions you will make when setting up your workplace retirement account. Here is a comparison of their tax features.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container" style="max-width:740px;">
    <div class="prose">
      <div class="callout"><strong>The core difference:</strong> A <strong>Traditional 401(k)</strong> gives you a tax break today by using pre-tax dollars, but you pay taxes on withdrawals in retirement. A <strong>Roth 401(k)</strong> uses post-tax dollars today, but your withdrawals in retirement are completely tax-free.</div>

      <h2>Traditional 401(k): Pay taxes later</h2>
      <p>With a Traditional 401(k), your contributions are deducted from your gross pay before income taxes are calculated. This lowers your taxable income for the year, reducing your current tax bill. The money grows tax-deferred, meaning you don't pay any taxes on investment gains while the funds are in the account. However, when you withdraw the money in retirement, the full amount (contributions and earnings) is taxed as ordinary income at your future tax rate.</p>

      <h2>Roth 401(k): Pay taxes now</h2>
      <p>With a Roth 401(k), you contribute post-tax dollars. Your taxable income for the year remains the same, meaning you get no immediate tax deduction. However, your money grows tax-free. When you withdraw the funds in retirement, you pay zero taxes on both your contributions and the investment earnings, provided you are at least 59½ years old and have held the account for at least five years.</p>

      <h2>Key differences side-by-side</h2>
      <table>
        <tr>
          <th>Metric</th>
          <th>Traditional 401(k)</th>
          <th>Roth 401(k)</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Tax break timing</td>
          <td>Immediate (pre-tax contributions)</td>
          <td>Future (tax-free withdrawals)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Required Minimum Distributions (RMDs)</td>
          <td>Yes, starting at age 73 or 75</td>
          <td>No (starting in 2024 for employer plans)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Employer Match Tax Status</td>
          <td>Taxed upon withdrawal</td>
          <td>Historically pre-tax, SECURE 2.0 allows Roth match options</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Contribution Limits</td>
          <td>Shared limit ($23,000 in 2024, plus catch-up)</td>
          <td>Shared limit ($23,000 in 2024, plus catch-up)</td>
        </tr>
      </table>

      <h2>Which one should you choose?</h2>
      <p>The decision boils down to your current tax bracket versus your expected tax bracket in retirement:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Choose Traditional if:</strong> You are currently in a high tax bracket and expect your tax bracket to be lower in retirement. Saving tax dollars today at a 24% or 32% rate and paying taxes later at a 12% or 15% rate is highly efficient.</li>
        <li><strong>Choose Roth if:</strong> You are early in your career, in a low tax bracket, and expect to be in a higher tax bracket when you retire. Paying taxes today at a lower rate to secure tax-free growth is a smart long-term move.</li>
      </ul>
